STRINGS: "We are sincerely grateful for your cooperation."
"For the sake of resolving this case,
please tell us what you know--"
"--Ms. Haruka Minase."
"...I have an appointment after this,
so I can't stay here for long."
"Also, I already told you everything I know.
I don't know whether I can help you or not..."
The time was a little after 15:30.
Ms. Haruka hadn't declared it,
but she implicitly appealed to be released quickly.
"We are sincerely grateful for your cooperation."
I uttered the same line one more time.
But this time, I looked into her eyes without haste.
Ms. Haruka showed a slight fear reaction.
I as well sent a message without needing to declare it.
'Did you really tell us everything you know?'
––it went.
Something about her reluctance to talk from the get-go bothered me.
She already stated what she knew.
Maybe that is true.
But regardless, I feel like she knows more than she's letting on.
"We understand that you don't have the time.
We'll make this as brief as possible."
"Just answer all of our questions
and this should be over swiftly."
Unfortunately for her, I have no plans of being lenient this time.
For the deceased Mr. Kazamori's sake.
Chief Kuroda, perhaps sympathizing with my feelings,
kept quiet by my side, only focusing his gaze at her.
"Even if you say that...
Er, can't we do this another day?"
"Why?"
"I mean, I did say I had business to take care of in a bit."
"What... is this?"
"My cell phone. Please, feel free."
"Eh? Uh, I don't understand what you mean."
"What I mean is, please use my cell phone
to tell the other party that you might be late for your appointment."
"And if they disapprove, please hand it back to me.
I shall explain that you're cooperating with the police
to help with solving a case."
Ms. Haruka noticeably bit her lip.
It's obvious that, no matter who they are, they'll back down
when a police officer joins the conversation.
Besides, by calling them, she'd also be telling us their phone number.
If that contact is a shady fellow,
or connected to her own ulterior motives regarding this case,
she'd have to be quite foolish to follow my suggestion.
"There's no way I can..."
I didn't fail to hear her faint mumbling.
Pretending not to have noticed, though, I put away the phone.
I'm convinced now.
She hasn't disclosed everything to us yet.
"I see. Then I ask for your prompt cooperation
so we may finish this as soon as possible."
"Okay. But I really don't know anything more--
I said everything I had to say about Mr. Tamura before."
"This isn't about Koutarou Tamura."
Then why did you call me here?
I mean, I don't understand."
"Did you not hear about the incident last night?"
"Last night...?
Sorry, but I slept late into the afternoon...
What happened?"
"Hiromu Kanaya did."
Her pupils contracted.
I didn't overlook that tiny disturbance.
"...W-what did he do?"
"Hiromu Kanaya murdered his own family, fled the police,
and during arrest, he fatally wounded an officer as well."
"You're joking... right?"
"I'll go straight to the point.
What is your relationship with Kanaya?"
"I don't know this guy. I have nothing to do with him."
"Kanaya was heard shouting your name.
Even if you are unrelated as you say,
we need proof."
"I'm saying I have no idea who that creep is!!
Are you listening to me!?"
She's resolute in her refusal to tell us the truth.
I made eye contact with Chief Kuroda.
The Chief replied stealthily.
It was the signal for me to 'do as I like',
so I interpreted it to my convenience.
"So you're not connected to him?"
"Yeah, that's right... I've no relation to him."
Once again I whipped out my cell phone
and placed it in front of her.
"Please, make a call.
Cancel your appointment."
"What is that supposed to mean!?
I told you I don't know anything!!"
"You're treating me like some sort of
This is tyranny!!
Listen to me seriously!!"
"Yes, we are listening to you seriously.
Which is why we want to talk to you."
"What you're saying and what you're doing is completely different!!"
"Is that so?
But here's the thing, Ms. Haruka--"
Without warning, I brought my face closer to hers.
"We don't call people here randomly.
Do you know what it's like to lose a good friend?"
I glowered at her with a fierce glare.
Ms. Haruka, with fear in her eye, immediately averted her gaze.
But I had to make doubly sure that she wouldn't
be able to act impertinent anymore.
"Or we could just gather everything about you by ourselves."
"And if something comes up, we'll take the necessary measures
so we can have a talk as thorough as we want."
"I think you know what'll happen if you try to do that."
"Are you trying to intimidate the police force?
Your statement now could be grounds for a threat charge."
"You'd go that low...!?!"
"I don't care what you think of me,
as long as you understand that I'm serious."
I applied mental pressure as many times as I needed
to make it known that I would never withdraw.
"I shall ask you again.
What is your relationship with Hiromu Kanaya?"
Even after all that, she upheld her silence.
But, finally, after letting out a deep sigh,
she began to speak.
"...He's a customer that took an interest in me."
She sighed once more.
The feeling of resignation found in the line, 'there, I said it',
seemed to have enveloped her.
"Customer...?"
"From a night shop. Bars, cabaret clubs, that sort.
Establishments you can find in the shopping district downtown.
Of course, they're all legal, just not properly recognized."
"In order to make my living, I work a part-time job in one of those.
Night after night... I thought pouring drinks for boring,
middle-aged geezers sprinkled with some flattery would be easy."
"But it wasn't that simple.
I'm fed up with being ogled by men I couldn't care less about,
and the constant sexual harassment as well, I hate it."
"But, the more my pent-up resentment grew,
more costumers requested me.
By the time I knew it, I had become number one."
"I don't know if I became talk of the town or what,
but the majority of customers came to meet me.
They'd give me all sorts of things, calling them presents."
"Things beyond the means of a regular college student.
Stuff I definitely couldn't bring or wear to my university at least."
"Maybe those men were under the belief that,
by giving me presents, they were putting a collar on me.
Idiotic, really."
"One of those stupid clients was Mr. Kanaya.
Even the shop I work in has class after a fashion,
which made him a very unbecoming customer."
"He sure didn't give off a clean impression in any way, shape, or form.
I'd imagine he would've been stopped at the door."
"The way he spent money was quite extravagant, you see.
The establishment has no reason to ban such a good customer."
"The manager would even prod me to make
frequent business calls to him.
Because, once I did, he'd show up at the store without fail."
"But that would only wear me down even more...!"
She looked downward and bit her lip.
Probably recalling all the things she did for him,
she must be pissed off.
If I was my former self,
I'd have worried for her and even proposed a break.
However, she hasn't reached the matters I want to know yet.
"He'd buy anything for me.
Request me all the time.
When I was being selfish, he'd listen to anything I'd whine about."
"A truly
Thanks to him, my hourly wage was raised.
But on the other hand, the stress increased too."
"You're a woman, so you should know.
How disgusting the things an unloveable man
would demand as repayment for all that are."
"But to the shop, he was their lucky guest of honor.
So they had me entertain him all the more."
"It was inevitable that he would get carried away and cross the line."
The woman who had kept talking without pause took a deep breath.
"Ms. Haruka, to you, Kanaya was the deplorable
regular customer of the club... I take it?"
"...If he was just that, do you think I'd keep my mouth shut?"
Ms. Haruka clenched her fist, and after repeatedly taking
a few deep breaths, resumed her account.
"On a certain after closing hours meeting,
that creep finally asked for my body.
His soliciting was the worst."
"'I've given you so much, so it's fine, isn't it?'
'You wouldn't like it if I stopped requesting you, would you?'
What an idiot! I wouldn't put my life on the line to keep that job."
"I'd rather die than sleep with that freak.
The first few times, I managed to evade it.
But... that day..."
"That day, he came and gave me an unexpected present."
"What was it?"
packed into a plastic bag."
"He said he wanted to buy me until next morning.
It put all his previous soliciting to shame."
"And did you, uhm,
go along with him?"
"Hey, I just want to know,
but if you were in the same situation,
what would you do?"
What would I do...?
